WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.349 --> 00:00:02.776
(pensive music)

00:00:02.776 --> 00:00:04.140
- [Staff Member] Order.

00:00:04.140 --> 00:00:06.320
- [Narrator] The race to
deliver your groceries faster

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:07.530
is speeding up.

00:00:07.530 --> 00:00:10.180
Demand for delivery services
boomed during the pandemic,

00:00:10.180 --> 00:00:11.900
and startups in the US and Europe

00:00:11.900 --> 00:00:13.720
are now promising to deliver items

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:15.340
in as little as 10 minutes.

00:00:15.340 --> 00:00:18.730
- So instead of you walking
to the grocery and all that,

00:00:18.730 --> 00:00:20.340
we are the ones that do that for you.

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:22.670
- [Narrator] So how can
they do so quickly something

00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:25.440
that often takes hours or even days?

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:28.220
They're operating out of
hyper-localized dark stores,

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:31.280
or mini warehouses
scattered around cities.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:33.490
- I really think of it as a store

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:34.810
that the customer just doesn't see

00:00:34.810 --> 00:00:36.490
and what they see is the app.

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:38.050
- [Narrator] Gorillas
is one of those startups

00:00:38.050 --> 00:00:39.320
that launched last year.

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:40.247
It already has dark stores

00:00:40.247 --> 00:00:43.270
and a fleet of delivery
workers in 40 European cities

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:44.850
and in New York.

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:48.300
Investment in ultrafast grocery
services lept several fold

00:00:48.300 --> 00:00:50.850
in the first six months of 2021.

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:53.490
But super fast delivery
means high operational costs

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:54.960
in a sector that's really crowded

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:56.662
with established players.

00:00:56.662 --> 00:00:59.410
And some analysts and
experts are skeptical

00:00:59.410 --> 00:01:01.030
about whether they can make money.

00:01:01.030 --> 00:01:03.060
- I don't see how it can be profitable.

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:04.930
- There is this big overarching question

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:07.660
of is this a sustainable business model?

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:09.460
And with this level of competition,

00:01:09.460 --> 00:01:11.370
what does the future look like?

00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:12.900
- [Narrator] We visited
dark stores in London

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:14.010
to see how these startups

00:01:14.010 --> 00:01:16.140
are pushing to deliver
groceries in minutes,

00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:18.690
and the long-term challenges
their businesses face.

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:23.380
While many delivery companies operate out

00:01:23.380 --> 00:01:26.310
of big warehouses or team
up with supermarkets,

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:28.440
dark stores are small and localized,

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:31.240
occupying between 2,000
and 5,000 square feet

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:33.270
to carry fewer products.

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:34.400
To use the service,

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:37.660
a customer places an order
through the app on their phone.

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:40.370
Staff at the dark store receive the order.

00:01:40.370 --> 00:01:41.610
(message dinging)
- [Staff Member] order.

00:01:41.610 --> 00:01:43.010
- [Narrator] And quickly
begin picking items,

00:01:43.010 --> 00:01:44.860
which are laid out in a way that speeds up

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:45.970
the packing process,

00:01:45.970 --> 00:01:48.020
like grouping heavier
items near each other

00:01:48.020 --> 00:01:49.230
so they can be packed first

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:50.730
and won't squash fresh produce.

00:01:50.730 --> 00:01:52.420
- If you're a pick
packer in the warehouse,

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:53.740
you hardly have to think,

00:01:53.740 --> 00:01:55.030
and you're simply going round

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:57.210
'cause everything is
organized and under control

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:58.800
through systems, et cetera,

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:01.420
and that allows you to
be very speedy basically.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:03.340
And then we come to you in minutes.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:06.110
- [Narrator] Alec Dent,
CEO of UK-based Weezy says

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:08.820
close proximity to customers
is the main reason apps

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:11.590
like Weezy and Gorillas
can deliver so quickly.

00:02:11.590 --> 00:02:14.460
Most dark stores are usually
within a one to two-mile radius

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:16.450
from households they deliver to.

00:02:16.450 --> 00:02:18.230
Grocery delivery sales have slowed

00:02:18.230 --> 00:02:20.600
since a peak during lockdowns last year

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:23.460
when online ordering became
a habit for many people.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:25.991
- This crisis accelerated
grocery e-commerce,

00:02:25.991 --> 00:02:27.940
and this kind of gave us a chance,

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:29.830
like a fast-start chance.

00:02:29.830 --> 00:02:32.040
- [Narrator] And Gorillas
says it still sees high demand

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:34.270
for deliveries, even as economies reopen.

00:02:34.270 --> 00:02:36.010
- Last year was a crazy time I think,

00:02:36.010 --> 00:02:37.980
so it's difficult to say
that this year's the same

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:39.960
but from a consumers' preference

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:41.094
and choice point of view,

00:02:41.094 --> 00:02:44.170
they still order as
frequently as they did before.

00:02:44.170 --> 00:02:45.120
- [Narrator] Gorillas has amassed

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:48.790
about 860,000 downloads
worldwide on Google Play

00:02:48.790 --> 00:02:51.054
since its launch in May last year.

00:02:51.054 --> 00:02:55.980
- It's another way of
reducing traffic in stores.

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:58.470
With time, I'm sure I might be

00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:00.620
the only thing happening later on.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:01.930
- COVID has shone a light

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:04.840
into traffic patterns and how people move,

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:06.370
and where they go for groceries,

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:08.920
and what people expect
in terms of convenience.

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:12.000
And a lot of these consumer
behaviors aren't going away.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.440
- [Narrator] The last-mile delivery sector

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:16.900
raised $16.2 billion in
venture capital funding

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:18.920
in the first half of 2021.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:22.227
- Our timing and our growth
was super, super to the point,

00:03:22.227 --> 00:03:24.840
and it attracted multiple investors.

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:26.240
- [Narrator] As of mid-2021,

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:28.700
Gorillas had raised nearly $350 million

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:30.670
in venture capital funding.

00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:32.270
Philadelphia-based Gopuff,

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:35.470
which already has more than
400 dark stores across the US

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:37.840
had received $2.4 billion.

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:40.940
But retail industry experts
like Phil Lempert caution

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:42.720
that the initial influx of investment

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:45.450
isn't always a sure sign
of long-term success.

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:48.740
- Venture capital firms
wanna invest in food.

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:50.010
They love food.

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:52.040
Whatever the idea is,

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:55.140
if you can combine food and convenience,

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:56.320
they're gonna throw money at it.

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:58.223
It doesn't mean it's gonna last.

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:01.560
- [Narrator] These companies
say that in the future,

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:03.970
they hope to make money from bigger orders

00:04:03.970 --> 00:04:06.280
but analysts warn that
the growing competition

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:08.420
on top of labor and transportation costs

00:04:08.420 --> 00:04:10.650
could hinder profitability.

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:12.880
- The core challenge in my opinion

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:15.305
of ultrafast delivery or rapid delivery

00:04:15.305 --> 00:04:16.750
is that it's fundamentally

00:04:16.750 --> 00:04:18.530
a very capital-intensive industry.

00:04:18.530 --> 00:04:19.790
It's a little bit of a departure

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:24.210
from the Uber Eats, DoorDash
software intermediary model.

00:04:24.210 --> 00:04:25.750
- Every time you wanna open a warehouse,

00:04:25.750 --> 00:04:28.160
it's a new real estate
lease that we're signing

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:30.180
or a team that we're building

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:31.790
or inventory that we're buying.

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:33.167
And so I think a lot of our money

00:04:33.167 --> 00:04:35.440
and our capital goes towards that.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:37.360
- [Narrator] Companies
like DoorDash in the US

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:38.800
and Deliveroo in the UK,

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:41.170
already known for their
restaurant delivery services,

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:43.500
have also partnered with
large supermarket chains

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:46.550
to bring customer
grocery items in minutes.

00:04:46.550 --> 00:04:48.780
And competition is only growing.

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:51.460
Bigger players like online
grocery giant Instacart

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:54.100
are also planning to build out
their own fulfillment centers

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:56.200
and launch ultrafast services.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:58.390
- Grubhub and Deliveroo,

00:04:58.390 --> 00:05:01.470
their business model is different.

00:05:01.470 --> 00:05:05.880
Their revenue is coming
from various sources

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:09.300
versus these startups
like Gorilla and so on

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:13.010
where I don't know where
their revenue's coming from.

00:05:13.010 --> 00:05:14.380
- The key question for me

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:18.430
is can these companies maintain
their sort of pricing power

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:22.280
as they face increasingly
robust competition from others.

00:05:22.280 --> 00:05:24.760
You need to build a
sustainable business model

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:26.860
that's curated for local markets

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:30.582
that can stand on its own
once the VC money dries up.

00:05:30.582 --> 00:05:33.332
(dramatic music)

